Data

Motivation

The motivation to collect the dataset was to use it to build a machine learning model to predict NCAA Division 1 menâ€™s tennis nationals matches. The dataset is created by Kartikeya Sharma on behalf of the final project for the CIS 670 Data Science class at the University of Oregon. There have not been any funding provided to create this dataset, though I need to purchase a $10 subscription of Universal Tennis Ratings to get the precise UTR ratings of the colleges and the players.

Composition

The data comprises of two different datasets, combined_features_with_national_qualifiers.csv and college_results.csv. The data is collected for the year 2021-2022 and contains all possible instances for that year.

combined_features_with_national_qualifiers.csv contains information regarding different feature sets for every NCAA D-1 college which offers menâ€™s tennis as a sport. The total number of rows for this dataset are 237. The columns/features for the above dataset are as follows:

name â€“> Name of the college tennis program

ita_school_id â€“> School Id used on the ITA tennis website

ita_team_id â€“> Team Id used on the ITA tennis website

latlng â€“> Latitude and Longitude of the location of the college tennis program

total_players â€“> Number of Players in a team for the year 2021-2022

total_dual_matches â€“> Number of dual matches played by a team for the year 2021-2022

total_points_won â€“> Total points won by a team for the year 2021-2022

total_points_lost â€“> Total points lost by a team for the year 2021-2022

power6_avg â€“> UTR average for the best 6 players on the team for the year 2021-2022

power6 â€“> Sum of the UTR for the best 6 players on the team on the date when the data is collected which is 5/22/2022

power6_high â€“> Best UTR on the team of the top 6 players when the data is collected which is 5/22/2022

power6_low â€“> Worst UTR on the team of the top 6 players the data is collected which is 5/22/2022

win_percentage â€“> Win percentage for the year 2021-2022

loss_percentage â€“> Loss percentage for the year 2021-2022

home_win_percentage â€“> Home Win percentage for the year 2021-2022

home_loss_percentage â€“> Home Loss percentage for the year 2021-2022

away_win_percentage â€“> Away win percentage for the year 2021-2022

away_loss_percentage â€“> Away loss percentage for the year 2021-2022

number_of_americans_percentage â€“> Percentage of american players on the team for the year 2021-2022

number_of_international_percentage â€“> Percentage of international players on the team for the year 2021-2022

countries â€“> Different countries represented on the team for the year 2021-2022

is_national_qualifier â€“> If a team has qualified for nationals or not

college_results.csv contains the information regarding all the D-1 matches played in 2021-2022. The total number of rows for this dataset is 2856. The columns/features for the above dataset are as follows:

team_0_id â€“> Team Id from the ITA tennis website for the team 0

team_1_id â€“> Team Id from the ITA tennis website for the team 1

won â€“> 0 or 1. If 0 team_0 won the match or If 1 team_1 won the match. This column will be used as a target variable.

There could be possibility of errors in the data collected. For example, the number of players are incorrect, players nationality is incorrect, the location of the college is incorrect, every match is not reported on the ITA website etc. The source of error would be the source of data but not the method of collection.

The sub population can be identified by columns such as countries or is_national_qualifier.

The data is not offensive, insulting or threatening. Also the data doesnâ€™t include any private information as everything is available online for the public to view.

Collection

The dataset is acquired/collected using the APIs of two websites which are https://colleges.wearecollegetennis.com and https://app.universaltennis.com/. You need to pay $10/month to acquire precise UTR ratingâ€™s data from the https://app.universaltennis.com/. The data is collected by writing python scripts and saving the collected data as csv files. The python scripts and csv files would be included in the final project submission.

The UTR data was collected on 5/22/2022. The College tennis results, demographics and win/loss data was collected over the span of a week between 5/16/2022 - 5/22/2022 as the API was timing out so I need to wait.

API documentation was not explicitly provided by either websites. I figured it out by inspecting the requests in the Google Chrome Devtools.

Preprocessing/Cleaning/Labeling

At first the dataset is preprocessed while collecting with python scripts and saved in the csv format. The scripts will be provided as part of the project.

The dataset was further processed with R scripts as the processes such as merge, select, remove etc are applied so that we can come up with the above two datasets. The scripts will be provided as part of the project. There was also some manual processing needed as the name of the colleges in the data received from the ITA website and the name of the colleges in the data received from the UTR website are different. I needed to find which names are different and manually correct them. No labeling was required as the data collected was labeled. The label in the question is basically which of the team won or loss the match.

Uses

There could be many different ways the data can be used:

  1. To predict the winner of a dual menâ€™s college tennis match.

  2. To gain insights about the demographics in menâ€™s college tennis.

  3. To predict the number of points a team will win in a year based on the different features available in the dataset.

There are currently no plans to make this data publicly available but if you want to use this data for your project, you can email me at ksharma@uoregon.edu. If in future, I make this data publicly available, it could be found on my github.

Maintenance

Currently there are no plans for maintaining this dataset but you can follow me on github for any updates.

Findings

  1. In the group Matches and Points, all the features looks normally distributed with slightly skewed on the right. This means some teams played a lot of matches during the year and it resulted into more points won as well as lost.

  2. In the group Universal Tennis Ratings power6_avg and power6 are skewed to the left while power6_high and power6_low looks more normally distributed. It means that there are less schools whose combined UTRs are less than 60.

  3. In the group Win/Loss Percentage, overall win and overall loss looks normally distributed. The Home Win (%) and Home (%) loss percent are skewed to the left and to the right respectively which means that it is less likely that team will loose at home or in other words it is more likely that the team will win at home. Away Win (%) and Away Loss (%) are skewed to the right and the left but not as much as compared to Home Win/Loss (%). This tells us that it is less likely to have more than 75% win on the road.

  4. In the group Player Demographics, the number are slightly skewed to the right but mostly the distribution looks normal or Gaussian. It tells us that it is less likely that the teams would have more than 15 players on the roster. By looking at the number of international or american percentage we can see that there are more international on a college team compared to the Americans.

I am amazed by so many different countries represented in NCAA Tennis, hence less look at where the athletes coming from and how many different teams a country is representing.

Incorporating features into college results data

In the previous section we explored the features of all the colleges in NCAA D-1 tennis. Now is the time to incorporate those features into college_results.csv. In this data, a row is a match where there are three columns team_0_id, team_1_id and won. Now we will be matching the data for each team and would be taking the difference of the features of two team i.e.Â feature(team_0) - feature(team_1).

college.matches.features = merge(college.matches, college.features, 
                                 by = intersect(names(college.matches), 
                                                names(college.features)),
                                 by.x = 'team_0_id', by.y = 'ita_team_id')
colnames(college.matches.features) = c(head(colnames(college.matches.features),3),
                                       paste0("team_0_", tail(colnames(college.matches.features),-3)))
college.matches.features = merge(college.matches.features, college.features,
                                 by = intersect(names(college.matches), names(college.features)),
                                 by.x = 'team_1_id', by.y = 'ita_team_id')
colnames(college.matches.features) = c(head(colnames(college.matches.features),24),
                                       paste0("team_1_", tail(colnames(college.matches.features),-24)))
college.matches.features = college.matches.features[, !(names(college.matches.features) %in% c('team_0_name', 'team_0_ita_school_id','team_0_latlng','team_0_countries', 'team_0_is_national_qualifier', 'team_1_name','team_1_ita_school_id', 'team_1_latlng', 
'team_1_countries', 'team_1_is_national_qualifier'))]
idx_vect=c(4:19)
colnames_vect = colnames(college.matches.features)
for(i in idx_vect){
  col_name_1 = colnames_vect[i]
  col_name_2 = colnames_vect[i+16]
  new_col_name = paste0(stri_replace(col_name_1, fixed='team_0_',''), '_difference')
  college.matches.features[,new_col_name] = college.matches.features[,col_name_1] - college.matches.features[, col_name_2]
  college.matches.features = college.matches.features[,!(names(college.matches.features) %in% c(col_name_1,col_name_2))]
}

Logistic Regression

Letâ€™s fit Logistic Regression model on the data and evaluate the results. But first define some functions which will help us to find various metrics such as Accuracy, F-1 Score, Precision and Recall.

performance_metrics = function(confusion_metrics){
  TP = confusion_metrics[1]
  FP = confusion_metrics[3]
  FN = confusion_metrics[2]
  TN = confusion_metrics[4]
  accuracy = (TP+TN)/(TP+FP+FN+TN)
  precision = TP/(TP+FP)
  recall = TP/(TP+FN)
  f1 = 2 * ((precision*recall)/(precision+recall))
  all.metrics  = c('accuracy'=accuracy, 
                   'precision'=precision, 
                   'recall'=recall, 
                   'f1'=f1)
  
  for (metric in names(all.metrics)){
    print(paste(metric, as.numeric(all.metrics[metric]), sep="---->")[1])
  }
  
  return(c(accuracy, precision, recall, f1))
}

The results of all the different Logistic Regression models trained on training data are given in the above tables.

When the models are tested on the Test Dataset (Test split of original dataset), the accuracy of all the models are in the range of 83.55 - 84.07 with the highest accuracy being achieved by Logistic Regression (Backward Selection AIC) i.e.Â 84.07. The recall and precision varies a lot, the range of recall is 86.28 - 90.74 and the range of precision is 84.64 - 89.30. F-1 score doesnâ€™t vary a lot and the highest F-1 score is associated with Logistic Regression (Backward Selection AIC) i.e.Â 87.76. AUC doesnâ€™t vary that much either and the highest AUC is associated with Logistic Regression (Backward Selection BIC).

When the model is tested on NCAA D-1 National Matches, one can no0t see a lot of variation in the metrics and the results are actually quite similar. Multiple models have same accuracy, highest F-1 score is obtained by Logistic Regression (Lasso) and the highest AUC is obtained by Logistic Regression (All Variables). One thing to note about these results is that the highest accuracy and F-1 scores have increased but the highest AUC have decreased when compared to the previous results.

Our first question was about the accuracy and we can see there are multiple models which have same accuracies. Hence to break the tie we can look at the alternative metric which is AUC. The highest AUC is associated with Logistic Regression (All Variables) but itâ€™s accuracy is not amongst the highest one so we can disregard it. Second highest AUC is associated with Logistic Regression (Backward Selection AIC). Hence we can conclude that Logistic Regression (Backward Selection AIC) is the best model here.

To answer our second question we need to look at the features selected by Logistic Regression (Backward Selection AIC) and they are:

  • total_players_difference
  • total_dual_matches_difference
  • total_points_won_difference
  • power6_avg_difference
  • power6_high_difference
  • power6_low_difference
  • win_percentage_difference
  • number_of_americans_percentage_difference

Now after looking at the above conclusions there are several questions which comes to the mind, they are:

1) Why the feature selection doesnâ€™t significantly improved the model?

2) Why the model was not able to predict the upsets correctly?

To answer the first question, we need to go back to our visualizations where we saw that there are some variables which have very strong correlation with each other. When you think of that then one might want to choose only those features which are not very strongly correlated with each other but when we try to do that in this situation there is no significant increase in the accuracy. Similarly Backward Selection did select the features which gave a little better performance than the model with all the features but again the performance was not substantial. And finally Lasso method did not give substantial improvements but did improve the recall substantially. The F-1 score remained similar as other models so I would not consider it substantial improvement.

What I think is happening here is that most of the original features in the datasets are actually not introducing noise to the dataset thus removing them is not increasing the performance substantially. Though the logistic regression with all variables is removing the variables which are 100% correlated to other variables in the dataset automatically.

While feature selection is computationally expensive it does give a more interpretable model as well a slightly better performance (at least in my case). To further improve the model one can try methods like Principal Component Analysis, Data Standardization etc.

To answer the second question we would first see what matches have been predicted wrong by our model and investigate if they are the upsets or not.

The highlighted rows are the upsets which the model did not predict correctly and you can see the upsets makes most of the data above. Now there are several reasons I can think of which makes the model not able to predict upsets in an accurate manner:

  1. Data doesnâ€™t include features about the teams performance in the previous NCAA championships. It has been evident that some team perform better than others in the championship for various reasons such as the experience of the coaches, experience of the players playing at high level tennis tournaments before coming to college, weather conditions etc.

  2. Data doesnâ€™t include the features about the difficulty of the schedule for a certain team. Some teams play very difficult schedule such as playing Top-20 teams in the country and then coming into the tournament with lower ranking but great match practice.

  3. Data is not realtime. The data we used in our prediction was static which means it was collected after the NCAA tournament. It could be possible that a day prior of the match, data could be different and the predictions can change.

To sum up, our model predicted the NCAA D-1 2022 Nationals Matches with 84.12% accuracy when Backward Selection (AIC) is applied to the original Logistic regression. To improve the model we should try other methods such as PCA, standardization etc and also should collect more features and realtime data.

Impact

There could be two major impacts of this work:

  1. Coaches using the model to recruit players and schedule matches.

College coaches can use this model and the features in the data to recruit the players which can closely resembles the features of a winning team. For example coaches can recruit players which can lead to a certain total UTR for a team or can recruit a certain percent of international players if they see team with high or low international players are having success. They can also use the model to determine the amount of matches and the difficulty of matches they should be playing so that they can come close to the features of a successful team. Also please note, the measure of success should be defined by the coaches themselves.

  1. Sports Bettors can use this model to improve their bets.

Sports better can use this model or build a new model based on this to improve their bets on the college tennis matches. A realtime model can be built based on realtime data with similar features I used to give a realtime prediction for a certain match as the features change after every match. Also please note I am not sure if it is ethical to use a Machine Learning model for betting or not.
